The paper deals with probabilistic degrees of Boolean functions, which is a topic in computational complexity theory. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) as it deals with the probability of agreement between a random polynomial and a Boolean function. The study of Boolean functions is closely related to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and data structures (cs.DS), making them likely sub-categories as well. Finally, the paper involves some geometric arguments, which could place it in the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category.
